<exercise id="fs-idp75965808">
<problem id="fs-idp137910768">
<para id="fs-idp53369552">What is the age of mummified primate skin that contains 8.25% of the original quantity of <sup>14</sup>C?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise xmlns:data="http://www.w3.org/TR/html5/dom.html#custom-data-attribute" id="fs-idp60953824"><problem id="fs-idp54190832">
<para id="fs-idp125426976">A sample of rock was found to contain 8.23 mg of rubidium-87 and 0.47 mg of strontium-87.</para>
<para id="fs-idm22718704">(a) Calculate the age of the rock if the half-life of the decay of rubidium by β emission is 4.7 <m:math><m:mo>×</m:mo></m:math> 10<sup>10</sup> y.</para>
<para id="fs-idp75993408">(b) If some <m:math><m:mrow>


<m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mn>38</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mn>87</m:mn></m:msubsup><m:mtext>Sr</m:mtext>

</m:mrow></m:math> was initially present in the rock, would the rock be younger, older, or the same age as the age calculated in (a)? Explain your answer.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idp172013760">
<para id="fs-idp58704368">(a) 3.8 billion years;
(b) The rock would be younger than the age calculated in part (a). If Sr was originally in the rock, the amount produced by radioactive decay would equal the present amount minus the initial amount. As this amount would be smaller than the amount used to calculate the age of the rock and the age is proportional to the amount of Sr, the rock would be younger.</para>
</solution>
</exercise><exercise id="fs-idm70032656"><problem id="fs-idp138527680">
<para id="fs-idp133778576">A laboratory investigation shows that a sample of uranium ore contains 5.37 mg of <m:math><m:mrow>

